Vault Access Log

Read the summary text. Select CLOSE when you are finished reviewing the summary text.

You review three months of Vault Access Logs.

 

In Branch A, you find that the vault is typically accessed 10 to 15 minutes after the start of the business day and two to three times throughout the day. The initial access is to allow the tellers to obtain their cash drawers and the subsequent accesses are typically to obtain more cash or, conversely, place cash in the vault to maintain appropriate cash levels on the teller line. Occasionally, the vault is also accessed for incoming and/or outgoing cash shipments. At the end of the business day, the vault is accessed again to return tellers' cash drawers.

 

The primary custodian (i.e., "A" key) is typically the head teller Sheila Thompson; however, in several instances the Branch Manager, Tom Gregory, acted as the primary custodian. In all instances, either Sheila Thompson or Tom Gregory signed as the primary custodian. The dual custodian (i.e., "B" key) was one of the various tellers. In all instances, tellers initialed the Vault Access Log as the dual custodian.

 

In Branch B, you find that the vault is typically accessed sometime in the morning and again at the end of the business day. Unlike Branch A, there was no evidence that the vault was accessed periodically throughout the day. The primary custodian (i.e., "A" Key) is the head teller Sonya Mills. There were no other initials appearing on the Vault Access Log.
